To obtain homozygous mutant ES cells , we introduced the -geo vector into HygR heterozygous ES cells .
Of 105 G418-resistant colonies tested , 49 were homozygous for <termsem="EG:434423"> ESG1 </term> deletion .
Northern blot and western blot analyses confirmed the absence of <termsem="EG:434423"> ESG1 </term> in these cells ( Figure 4C ) .
In 29 clones , the -geo vector had replaced the HygR vector , such that the cells remained heterozygous .
In the remaining 27 clones , the -geo vector was integrated at non-homologous sites .
<termsem="EG:434423"> ESG1 </term> - / - ES cells exhibited normal morphology ( Figure 5A ) .
These cells also proliferated at a speed comparable to that of the control ( heterozygous and wild-type ) cells ( Figure 5B ) .
<termsem="EG:434423"> ESG1 </term> - / - cells differentiated normally after the removal of leukemia inhibitory factor ( Figure 5B ) or retinoic acid treatment ( not shown ) .
When transplanted into hind flanks of nude mice , these cells produced teratomas , tumors containing components of all three germ layers ( Figure 5C ) .
These results indicate that <termsem="EG:434423"> ESG1 </term> is dispensable for the self-renewal properties and pluripotency of ES cells .
